I fell in love in New Zealand. With this tree. More than one thousand years in this spot, meanwhile in my life I struggle to meditate for five minutes. 
I lay on my back looking up and felt no more important than a passing breeze. Truly my heart aches leaving her behind. What a wild and wonderful thing to feel for a tree.
There are so many steps in getting to a finished book. I’ll never be the same. #GoodForAGirl

10 Year Anniversary Alert! Yes! When we signed @fleshmanflyer on January 1, 2013 (code named ‘f-bomb’), it was truly Oiselle’s coming out party in terms of being a legit brand that was breaking into elite running – whether we were invited or not! What I had no way to predict at the time, however, was that the next ten years would be an absolute hit parade of incredible moments, countless miles, and supernova levels of run love. We heart you, Fleshman! Thank you for always believing in the bird, and here’s to many more!
— @oiselle_sally

10 years ago, at the height of my racing career, I leapt off the splintery plank that is the male-centered sports industry and took flight with Oiselle. It was, without a doubt, the best decision of my career, and one of the best of my life overall. We have spent the last decade centering women in sports, challenging norms, poking the bear, and modeling new ways of doing things that have changed the industry as a whole. I’m so proud of what we have done together as a community. The experience of the last decade with Oiselle has made me into a person who refuses to settle for “that’s just how it is” in all parts of my life, in our greater community of running, in sport, and beyond. Thank you isn’t possibly enough, but I’ll say it anyway. Thanks for taking a chance on me in 2013. And thank you for every day that has come after. Here’s to many more.
— @fleshmanflyer

ONE WEEK TIL PUB DAY!
Such a dream endorsement from David Epstein! 
Most of you are accustomed to my lyrical voice on here and in blogs, and while that exists in my book, both the science and the urgency of the topics required it’s own voice. I wanted to bring research to life, bring people into my embodied experience, and not linger (but sometimes I can’t help it). The pacing is fast, the urgency apparent. I wanted it to be hard to put down, hard to look away, and imperative to pass along to someone you care about. You’ll have to decide for yourself if it does what I set out to do. Thanks David for taking time to read my story and for the great endorsement! 

If you haven’t read his book “Range: Why Generalists Triumph in a Specialized World,” it’s one of my top non-fiction reads of all time, influencing my life, my coaching, and my parenting. Check it out!

A few months ago, I had the absolute pleasure of sitting down with 14 incredible humans for dinner. Every single one of them inspires me to be a better human, and it was such a gift.

While each of them are a fearless community leader who has made our world a better place, @fleshmanflyer is the person I have looked up to the longest. She has given me the courage to speak up about things that matter countless times. (I even channeled my inner Lauren when I asked Malcolm Gladwell a tough question!) 

And during that dinner, having just read her book, Good For A Girl (comes out Jan 9th, go get it, it is beautifully done, and 100% recommend), I welcomed the opportunity to ask the group what they had learned in their time in the community. Lauren’s answer was just what I needed to hear (although you will have to go listen yo the podcast to hear it, she’s on @runningforreal episode for the week at runningforreal.com), and her book, spoke to so many things I would never in my wildest dreams have believed she struggled with too. I thought she was the one person of all who wouldn’t have fallen into those traps. But she did, and I admire the hell out of her for the deep dive she did into herself to write this book, to change the landscape for women and girls to come. If you are a coach, or work with women, this is an absolute MUST. Go get yourself a copy, this is powerful stuff ❤️

It’s Launch Day for Good for a Girl! A book is a collection of the talents and hard work of so many. I’m grateful to everyone who played a part in this work. And I’m absolutely floored by the support and love from my community today and in the lead up! Oh and did I mention I was interviewed by TERRY GROSS on FRESH AIR today??? What is life? I hope the media opportunities I’ve been given within and outside the sports world help this book reach whoever may benefit from it, and I hope this work serves the sport and people we love. 
Your very tired and happy Instagram friend,
Lauren

@fleshmanflyer is on the most recent episode of the I’ll Have Another Podcast!

Lauren Fleshman’s new book, Good for a Girl, is out now! Lauren has had a big career in so many different areas – running, entrepreneurship, coaching, etc. In her book, Lauren goes through all of that!

Lauren ran for Stanford where she was a 5-time NCAA Champion and 15-time All-American. Lauren went on to run professionally for Nike where she won 2 USA Championships and was on 5 World Championship teams. Lauren’s career had a lot of ups and downs and we chatted about that in this episode!

Lauren is an entrepreneur through and through. She is the founder of @pickybars, hosts running retreats, and is the coauthor of the popular @believetrainingjournal. 

🎧 Check it out - you can find this episode on any podcast app when you search for the “I’ll Have Another Podcast” or at SandyboyProductions.com

Dumbfounded. Optimistic. And most of all, SO GRATEFUL to everyone who is reading, gifting, sharing, online reviewing, elevating, and supporting this work. Making bestseller lists is not something I thought would happen for a women’s sports book written by someone who isn’t @mrapinoe or a seasoned capital W Writer. But it has. And because it has, more people will discover it, and there will be more people aware, invested, and fired up to imagine and work toward a better future. 

This book has done very well in independent bookstores where it’s the #15 bestseller in Non-fiction on the Indie Bestseller List in its first week. New York Times ranks it #10 in Non-Fiction Hardcover and #13 in combined print and ebook. I mean what is happening????

I learned long ago in running (maybe you read about it) that a label someone else gives you doesn’t define you or the worth of your contributions. It’s a milestone I’m thrilled we’ve reached, and y’all made it happen. Here’s to the book finding the hands it’s meant to find, and this list making it a little bit easier to stand out in all the noise. If you’re looking for a way to help the lifespan of the book, genuinely sharing with your friends and writing online reviews (Goodreads, Amazon, etc) make a huge difference. 

What. A. Moment. 

I hope you feel my gratitude in your bones. I’m radiating it with so much love. Thank you for this moment of celebration.

Tomorrow, @lauriewagner is having me on as a guest in an online class on writing about family.

When: Friday, January 27th, 8-9:30 PST. (You can access the video within 24 hours if you can’t be there live.)

You’ll leave our session with:

Ideas on how to use Wild Writing to dig deeper into the emotional complexity of a scene, and thoughts on how to write about family in a way that honors the truth of what went down, while honoring the humanity of the people involved. 

Laurie is a masterful truth teller, and her daily work for years upon years has been helping people do the same in community. A class with Laurie and Marianne Elliott is what got me started on this whole path. Writing about forbidden territory liberates. 

We were originally scheduled to do this in November but I got sick and had to reschedule. Now I’m healthy and eager and I hope you’ll join us! 

https://27powers.org/lauren-fleshman/

The audiobook feedback has been fantastic, and I’m so glad I recorded it myself so you can hear me tell it. I would be honored if you downloaded it and let it into your mind and heart, or gave it as a gift to someone who may be less likely to buy it themselves. ♥️

Self-portrait of a woman feeling far less alone, knowing the work is doing work in the minds and hearts of thousands of others. Thank you for your posts and messages. I love hearing what the book is bringing up for you, the learnings and unlearnings, the story you once believed about yourself or others that you’re rethinking, what it changes for you, or what it doesn’t change. I love hearing all of it. ✨

Big news on the home front: After 20+ years, we have decided to end our romantic partnership. We will continue on in the truest expression of us - loving co-parents, best friends, confidants, and family.

Our relationship has evolved significantly a few times over the last decade toward this state, so while this news might feel sudden to some, it’s been in the works for a while with the support of a small group of family and friends. Still, processing this change has of course been hard, with lots of sadness and grief, and we know that will continue to ebb and flow. But there has also been a feeling of relief in a way, as we’ve accepted that friendship and loving co-parents is in fact the truest form of our relationship now and beyond. 

We are so proud of us. We fell in love as teenagers, we grew up together, we have two fantastic children together, we grew a business, adventured, and built community. We have maintained love, respect and support for one another through so many changes and life stages, including this one. Our families will always be family, and we are and will remain good friends committed to the well-being of each other and our kids. There is a lot to look forward to, both as a family and separately. We like one another’s company and share community, so if you have an event you want to invite us both to, please do! Just don’t be surprised if one or both of us brings a date :)

Lauren and Jesse

It is critical to listen to the lived experiences of Black people experiencing over-policing. White people, if you find yourself defending the police presence because these folks were reportedly in the street cheering and were potentially obstructing other runners, take a minute and examine that. How much police presence would a group of white people doing the same thing receive? What might the conversation sound like? How would a couple white women in Wellesley be spoken to if they were over the barricade by these police officers? White people have a habit of responding to Black experiences with “but they did ___.” People of every race break the rules, stretch the rules, claim space. But not everyone gets the same response when they do it. And that tells you what America’s priorities are. Who we care the most about “keeping in line.” And what we feel is necessary to do so. This level of response shows a fear of Black people, and an entitlement to intimidate them. I’m angry to hear this happened to @_mr1derful and his friends. And I’m glad he shared it and that @alisonmdesir amplified it and called on the running community to really look at this experience. This is not an isolated incident, it is part of the larger problem of Black people being made to feel unwelcome and unsafe in white spaces, and specifically in our “running is for everyone!” community, at the “pinnacle event” for our sport, no less. To my fellow white people, please spend less time searching for justification of police behavior and messaging Black people to correct their feelings and lived experience, and more time listening and thanking those who are willing to show us what needs addressing in order to fulfill the promise of our sport, and nation.

There are so many enormous things happening in my life right now, all at once. They’re happening so fast that I can’t stop to tell the stories, but I want to and will find a way over the next few days as things *appear* to be letting up temporarily. 
This is a moment I cherished during Boston Marathon weekend. This brewery event was the first @oiselle community event I’ve attended since the partnership with @runjanji was announced. And it was a truly magical example of teamwork and community. Looking through the album of photos, I found myself pausing on ones where I feel love and admiration. Our leader @auntymouse’s energy on the mic was a catalyst to bring out the best in the panelists. @sallycbergesen was to my right, the woman who started it all and radiates power and poise. @karagoucher is so loving and accessible, making each of us want to find our why, and take a stand. The sold out event was full of some familiar faces who have influenced me and many new ones, and there was an energy in the room that can only be felt, not spoken. The best I can attempt to say is it feels like an openness to one another and a willingness to hold the mirror up to ourselves to see where we can grow, with far less defensiveness than most spaces inspire. I would love to do more of these with this team. Thank you to everyone who came!

As @alisonmdesir says, it’s not a moment but a MOVEMENT for women runner/authors. She led us this season with Running While Black and the movement has continued to build. One by one we shift the algorithm that buries books by women athletes. Having our books released in close proximity, supported heavily by readers, will hopefully make things easier for future female sports writers whose work has been suppressed. There are many books that came before ours that paved the way, helping us to believe in our work and see it through. The success of this season of books (including @des_linden @bonniedford NYT bestseller Choosing to Run, Des was pre-race here) is a tipping point. My ask is to please continue supporting authors in this space who don’t fit the white man mold that has dominated it. Buy their books too, by all means. But may we all remember that books by women and people of color and especially women of color encounter so many obstacles in getting published, getting promoted, and getting read, and those obstacles have nothing to do with the quality or power of the work. When you buy books from historically unrepresented voices, you change things. And if you’re a white man buying these books, I just want to recognize that the world has told you our messages aren’t useful to you in overt or subtle ways for all or much of your life and yet you engage. Your engagement matters, it is a form of allyship that helps change the algorithm, along with your heart. Thank you. Whoever you are, if you haven’t read or listened to all of these yet, I encourage you to. There are so many women’s stories that are fantastic and published by smaller presses and don’t get the same media hype. Please don’t assume that means they aren’t great books. There is a whole system of gatekeepers and privilege in publishing like every other part of society. If you have been affected by a book by an author who is traditionally under celebrated, please know that your purchase and review and endorsement makes a difference. I’m so proud to be a part of this movement. Thank you to the @teambaa for the stage at the @bostonmarathon expo, and to @alisonmdesir for making it happen. The convo was 💯

I’ve spent a great deal of my life working hard to stay in my lane. The known path, the proven path, felt like the safest way forward toward success and happiness. And for a long while I thought forward was the only way worth traveling. Looking around or inward or god forbid backwards could be dangerous because it could throw me off course. And it did, and it didn’t. 

Giving up the safety of lanes is when I started to gradually see things as they are in the world and in the mirror, and it allowed me to really become. Among many things, it made me an advocate. A writer willing to be brave. It allowed me to poke the bear and demand better for people in girls’ and women’s sports. To complete the toughest project I ever dared to start, and share it. It made me willing to see and live into the fullness of my identity, and to fall in love with this incredible human.

Eva (@lezglam) shows me daily the ways beauty, love, joy, and creativity thrive in the margins and beyond. She is a talented filmmaker, an industry changer @catalystfilmcollective, a mom who somehow has the energy to play tag, a magnet for wise friends and novel experiences, an extroverted maximalist, and a wonderful partner. She can find a way to capture the saturated sunset in a storm, and ground the wildest heart in the room with a long embrace. Entering into something this big and new with a mix of families in our 40’s has been inspiring and scary for both of us. Heading into summer I’m feeling excited, proud of what we are building, and open to what this tender stage of life will bring ✨

This kid is 10. TEN. On the 10th, at just after 10pm, it was official. A golden golden birthday. 

Jude woke up from a dream a week ago, and sketched out the basic design of his dream cake, which we made together. Three layers: cookie, rice Krispy treat, and chocolate cake. Parkour course on top made of candy. He wanted a slumber party with kids ranging from kinder to 5th grade, and Jesse and I made it happen at my new house, reading seven (!) boys bedtime stories, and taking turns standing guard on the back porch until the tents finally got fully quiet at 11pm 🤯. They were up pillow fighting before six, full on Lord of the Flies, climbing my fences and trees pissing off the snoozing neighbor (whoops!) until I put Grizzy and Lemmings on where they squished onto the sofa, now united with the five and six year old who slept inside, until the ebelskivers and bacon were ready. They were so happy laughing together. Jesse took the crew to the local field to release some energy while the house got put back together. By 9am the kids were all picked up. It was so awesome to make his golden birthday wishes come true. He brought together such a sweet group of imaginative wild things I’m proud to know a little better. And wow, I slept 11 hours the next night. Add it to the list of very occasional things one does😂. #NoRegrets. 
My favorite part was finishing Princess in Black (their request) at 10:03pm, Jude’s official birth time, and Jesse and I reaching in the tent to put our hands on Jude’s shoulders to wish him a happy golden birthday, seven boys all around him, looking on, appreciating their friend. 

We are so proud of you, Jude. These are sweet times, and we know it.

I’ve been short on words lately. This summer I took some time off to recover from writing and releasing Good for a Girl, and to absorb the changes in my family structure and life. As usual, everything seems to happen at once, but this is the first time I’ve given myself “a summer” since I was a student. And like when I was a student, summer has been about reconnecting with family and loved ones…and about stretching out time. I have been playing a lot. Traveling. Being away from my phone. My world has gotten smaller in a way that’s grounding. 
There were many times I came on here to share one photo or other from my beautiful and sometimes painful summer, but I could produce no words to go along with it. Everything felt swirly and hard to pin down. “What does this photo represent?” I’d ask myself. “What do I want to share about this?” And I couldn’t answer because I didn’t know myself. I couldn’t interpret my own life clearly, even for myself. And so I moved on, another draft in the folder that will never be posted. I’ve considered a summer photo dump post, but now I’m thinking I’ll just keep this summer for me. 
What brought me to this app today was wanting to share these photos of Jude that move me, and instead of having my usual loss of words, I found myself typing ones that have nothing to do with the photos. Or maybe they do. All summer, Jude has been my muse to live in the present. He is growing up fast now, and I can feel how important my mothering is to him. And maybe that’s it. That mothering energy is also something I’ve been giving myself. I see him blooming. I feel me growing new tender roots. I will bloom one day soon, too.

I received incredible news today 😱🥹 My book has been longlisted for the 2023 William Hill Sports Book of the Year! 
Called “The worlds most valuable sportswriting prize,” the @bookieprize has a history of recognizing the most important and groundbreaking books in sports. This year, out of the eighteen books longlisted for the @BookiePrize, six were written by women. This is twice as many as previous years, which feels like a tipping point. 
My book lives in the nexus of two male dominated fields: sports and sportswriting. A book highlighting both the invisible wounds of female athletes and the struggles of women in industries built around male norms making the longlist for excellence in sportswriting is a dream. Given the subject matter, my book is still the kind of book many men won’t even pick up. Books written by women in all genres are still widely put in a cultural box of “women’s books,” making it difficult for them to get more widely platformed. And since it takes more than women alone to solve the problems facing them, I’m so grateful to all of you, of all genders, who are actively breaking that barrier down. 
The shortlist will be announced in a month or so, which awards a cash prize and a leather bound copy of your book. And then a winner is announced in November, (for anyone interested in following sportswriting awards). From what I can tell online, I can’t see any previous winners over the 35 years that were stories written by a woman about a female athlete or women’s team 🤯. 
Congrats to my team @emilycunning11 @daniel.greenberg4456 @lgrlit @penguinpress @penguinrandomhouse @viragopress. I have the best team. #whsboty #genderinsport #womenssports #oiselle #goodforagirl

Happy Birthday, Zadie 🥰 
A little house party, a lemon poppyseed cake, wonderful friends, a look at some photos and videos of your first couple days on Earth, and a lot of Barbie…Twas a very good birthday. I love getting to know this bright, silly kid.

Thank you to the judges for selecting Good for a Girl to be on the shortlist for the William Hill Sports Book of the Year! Four of the six books are by women this year, which is unprecedented! Check out @bookieprize to see the finalists. Winner of the @bookieprize is announced November 30th in London. I know it’s a long shot, but it’s fun to dream. From what I can tell, only one previous winning book was about a female athlete or sport (Beryl, by Jeremy Wilson), and I don’t believe a woman’s memoir has ever won. Maybe this is the year? Maybe it will be someone’s story who is reading this right now, one that hasn’t been written yet. Women: keep telling your stories! It is thrilling to be part of this moment in women’s sports history. We are experiencing growth in every meaningful way, across every sport, and yet the problems I talk about in this book will persist and expand through that explosive growth unless we change how we approach and respect the athletes who play. Regardless of the outcome at the ceremony, I am feeling a pull to fly across the ocean to attend as a way of honoring the work that came before me and show gratitude for the institutions and individuals taking books about women’s sport seriously. I’d love to meet the other authors and my UK agent and publisher @viragopress in person. I haven’t booked travel yet but I’m thinking about it!! #whsboty 
Thanks again to @emilycunning11 for your work on this book♥️

I know you’ve heard me talk about this book a lot this year, and it gets old when people do that. A book is a HUGE lift and this one was decades in the making and the impact is real. Thanks for sticking with me, amplifying the work when it feels good to you, and caring about the future. 
I wish y’all could read my inbox messages. What I’m most proud of with this book is the way it has shifted people’s beliefs: about themselves, their history, their future, their daughters, sisters, patients, athletes, wives. Thank you to everyone who has sent me a note, an impact statement, a story, or said hello and told me in person so I could understand.
If you haven’t picked up a copy yet, a little reminder that the hardcovers won’t be around much longer, and you can find them at a discount many places online right now. My local bookstore, @roundaboutbooks will be stocking signed hardcover copies for the holidays, which is the only way to get a signed one outside of an in-person book event (looking at you Phillidelphia Marathon!) Just indicate in the notes at checkout @roundaboutbooks that you want a signed copy. 
In the coming weeks, we will be strategizing promoting the January paperback release, which will make the book more accessible price-wise. I see the paperback release as a big opportunity to reach teams as a way to inspire healthy choices and intervene in harmful social norms as early as possible. Already, maternity funds have been created, non-profits have been started, coaches mental health groups have been facilitated, and family and team cultures have been shifted. And I know that I’ve only reached a teeny weenie fraction of the sports community. 
I’ve got one more chance to cast a wider net, and I need your help. There are so many smart and creative people following me here. If you have any ideas as to how I could reach new people, and especially teams efficiently, or incentivize the gifting of books to teams by motivated parents, or academia leads, or media ideas, or anything else that might help, please comment below! Or DM me. And feel free to tag someone wise or share this post if your community might have ideas to contribute. I appreciate you ❤️

Let’s do this Philadelphia! Pace team on duty!

Something really special is happening in Philadelphia. A week ago I spent time there for Marathon Weekend, and I haven’t stopped moving since. But it feels important to share about it because I was blown away. There were four events to choose from over two days (8k, 13.1, kids races, 26.2), the half and full sold out, there were about 35,000 participants over the weekend, the energy was big, joyful and exciting without feeling like we’re cattle like in some big marathons, and the weather was perfect. 

I paced the half marathon at 1:59 pace alongside pacing pros Allison and Michael, and my removeable flyout long sleeve and pocket jogger shorts were the perfect gear choices. Throughout the weekend I worked alongside @aliphine @jwardy21 @bartyasso  on speaker panels and meet and greets, and I can’t say enough great things about those humans. I’ve known about the three of them for years, but we’d never met. All three of them are so open hearted, authentic, and generous, and together we met wonderful folks in the running community. 

I got to meet @300poundsandrunning and @iamlshauntay at the @runslowaf booth and Martinus signed his book for me, which is a great resource that centers people who have traditionally felt like outsiders in the sport of running, and his advice is really good.

The staff behind the event had their hearts all the way in it, especially when faced with challenges. I’ve never seen that degree of female, nonbinary, and queer representation in leadership before, and it deepened my belief in what’s possible when leadership is diverse. It is such a hard job pushing for change, because like any other industry, once you declare you care, you are held to an even more impossible standard of perfection. @kathleentitus, I’m so impressed with your leadership. Crystal and Al, thanks for taking such good care of us and working tirelessly for the event. 
Long story short, I’d definitely recommend @philly_marathon. It’s already on my calendar for next year.

We are going to LONDON!!! 4 hours delayed out of Bend already but it looks like we’ve been rebooked and will eventually get there tomorrow sometime! Scroll through to see who we are picking up at Seattle airport on the way 😍

We have four days in London and are staying near Covent Garden. We already have the @bookieprize award ceremony planned on Thursday (🤞🏼) and Wicked on Saturday, but the rest is yet to be determined! Looking for recommendations for good sushi, a fun high tea experience, and anything especially cool around holiday season! Stay tuned for stories in London, and thanks for all the good vibes❤️

We won the Sports Book of the Year Award! ?!?! 🤯 I’m still trying to process it! Thanks @bookieprize for putting on a beautiful award show and party. I haven’t felt butterflies like that in a long time. 

Women have been telling their stories for a long time, but having these storytellers encouraged, supported, and widely celebrated isn’t as common as it should be. In fact, this is the first book by a woman about women’s sports to win the #whsboty in its 35 years. 
6 years ago when Zadie was born, I doubt this book would have been published with much support. Things are changing fast in women’s sport, with record investment and viewership. But if we don’t continue to address the root problems, they will only expand as women’s sport grows, harming even more people. My greatest hope is that by the time Zadie reads this book, the topics have become so irrelevant that she asks herself “how the hell did this book win Sports Book of the Year?” We got to work, kid. 

Thank you @viragopress, @sarahsavitt @katyaellis and Caspian Dennis for your support of this book in the UK, for your help bringing me here, and for the delicious pre-awards breakfast together. Thank you @penguinpress for all your hard work at home! 

Thank you to the judges for your consideration and support, and Chair Alyson Rudd for continually pushing for increased women’s representation. Thank you to the @bookieprize for your steadfast support of sports writing and your championing of women’s sports and voices.

Thank you to Jude and Eva for making the trip to London an adventure, and thank you to Jesse and Zadie cheering back home, and to my family and community for all the support ❤️

I’m finally going to sleep now.

social_posts.post_text: Four days is not nearly enough in London. But we packed it as full as we could! Here’s a little mix of photos we managed to stop and take. We explored by tube and by foot, and it was COLD. I should have packed a puffy. Professional highlights include the @bookieprize ceremony, being interviewed for Sky News, and brunch with the stellar Virago Team at @thewolseley 😊. Fam highlights include just wandering around, the Charlie and the Chocolate Factory themed high tea (Jude), sushi and an underground alien themed arcade in Camden, eating in a 400 year old pub with delicious food that magically had a table for us, taking too long in the science museum and discovering our tube station was closed and having to RIP through the streets of London in a black cab to make it in time for @wicked_musical while the cabbie ranted about politics, and all the together time. The only real bummer was my cold the week before turned into laryngitis keeping me up all night coughing on top of the jet lag the entire trip. I had no voice half the time and a croaky one the other half, so interviews were very hard and painful. I woke up in my own bed this morning (at 3:45am) feeling quite a bit healthier, feeling blown away by how much better age 10 is for travel than anything before it, and feeling so grateful Eva is in my life.

The good news keeps coming! @audible named Good for a Girl one of the top 18 bios and memoirs of 2023!! I put my heart into recording it, and often had to ask the producers for breaks to let the shakes pass through me. 
If you’re an audiobook person, or someone you wish would read this book is more of an audiobook person, I recommend this version. You can gift someone a credit on audible for $15 on their website. I absolutely love my audible subscription and wish I hadn’t waited so long to get it. You can also download the audio version from the library.

My trip to London for the @bookieprize with @viragopress is one I’ll never forget. What a thrill to receive these sneak peek sealed books. Still pinching myself. If you see one in the wild in the coming year, send me a pic 💕
If you’re interested in a signed book for the holidays, especially if you’re not on a strict December 25th deadline, place an order through @roundaboutbooks and we’ll get you covered.

Seven miles of running interrupted by aha moment walk breaks while listening to @glennondoyle interview Lindsay C Gibson, author of Adult Children of Emotionally Immature Parents. It’s safe to say emotional maturity wasn’t my dad’s biggest strength, and there were good reasons for that, and it was really helpful hearing how internalizers like me tend to be impacted into adulthood. I’m such an extreme internalizer that during the podcast I had trouble remaining focused on how I was impacted and instead constantly interrogated myself for signs that I am an emotionally immature parent. Which of course I am sometimes. 
How powerful it is to notice patterns so you can break them, and to notice and appreciate the ones that are already broken in the rear view. 
Running is good for so many things, including the old standby as a way to make time for learning and reflecting while stuck way out on a trail with no escape.

Nothing better than a spontaneous warm winter day outside in the woods, a rope swing, and a frozen puddle. It’s been a while since I approached New Years Eve with neutrality. The last few years I’ve been counting down the days for the promise of a turned page. This one feels like just another day on the horizon, and I like it.
Tomorrow is paperback pub day!!! And I’m making myself wait one more day to tell you why I’m so excited about it!

Nothing shaped me more in high school than my sports teams. During a time of life when young people are differentiating themselves from their families of origin, looking for where they might fit in the larger world, a team exposes you to different kinds of people and puts you in cahoots for a common goal. A great team is a place to experiment with identity, be playful, and learn how to win, lose, and make meaning inside the ordinary. It is also a place where harmful ideas can implant themselves and make a home, ideas that erode everything from confidence to performance to bone density—ideas that take away from the ultimate positive power of sports participation. 

Today is the paperback publication date of my book Good for a Girl. It comes with a much more accessible price, and bonus material in the form of discussion questions and an interview to make the book more useful, especially for teams. Not just teams of athletes but people taking a team approach to their care: groups of parents, coaches, administrators, health care professionals. Readers have been telling me all year that the conversations that came from reading the book have been powerful, and the new material is designed to help encourage more of that. 

Here’s the exciting part! 

My publisher and I put together a special promotion to get this paperback book into as many hands as possible with an eye on teams: buy 25 paperback books and you get 38% off and a 30 minute zoom meeting with me for your team or group. When my schedule reserved for free speaking spots fills up, I’ll remove the free zoom meeting part from the product description page but the huge team discount will remain. 
Other groups that could qualify: a parent group or booster club, a school athletic department…feel free to ask below if you’re wondering. I know 25 books is a lot, but to make it feasible with shipping efficiencies and the time it takes to make it work, that’s the minimum number we can do. The good thing about books is they never expire until the ideas do, and we have a few years of work ahead before that happens. Let’s make that happen!

Head over to laurenfleshman.com for the link to the special offer! Thank you 💕

Team is everything. To celebrate the paperback release of Good for a Girl, my publisher is offering 38% off and a free video chat with me and your team when you buy 25 copies or more (offer is limited). Go to laurenfleshman.com to get started ❤️

Thank you to my amazing coaches and teammates for some of the best memories of my life, and for leading me toward a lifetime of movement. Let’s make this environment healthy and long lasting for all.

I’d love to see a reel of your high school sports memories. Tag me ❤️

In today’s episode of The Alpha Girl Confidence Podcast, I sat down with Lauren Fleshman @fleshmanflyer who is one of the most decorated American distance runners of all time, a mom, entrepreneur, coach, and author of the best sports book of 2023, Good for a Girl: A Woman Running in a Man’s World.

In this convo, we delve into thought-provoking topics surrounding systemic issues in women’s sports, the impact of puberty on athletic performance, and the prevalence of disordered eating habits among female athletes. 

Check out to full conversation wherever you get your podcasts or via link in bio AND make sure to check out Lauren’s book, Good for a Girl! 📚
